Paper 6 v2.1: refine Bloom-music claim in section 4

Absorb the Korsyn 1991 / Straus 1990 programme of Bloomian musicology as
corroborative rather than counter-evidence of the structural relocation.

Prior v2.0 framing said the interpersonal agon model "maps poorly" to
music, architecture, and mathematics - overstated for music, where
Korsyn (Music Analysis 1991) and Straus (Remaking the Past, Harvard 1990)
are the canonical systematic applications. v2.1 reframes: these analyses
are productive but recurrently strain toward structural vocabulary at the
moments where the interpersonal reading is least load-bearing, which
reads the Korsyn-Straus programme as documenting pressure toward the
structural relocation rather than as a domain where the Bloomian model
succeeds. Architecture and mathematics remain as domains where the
interpersonal model simply doesn't fit; music is now treated as a domain
where it partially fits and partially strains, with the strain visible
in the literature's own structural vocabulary.

